{
  "doc_id": "21483",
  "text": "The commercially available cylindrical mirror is made out of 10 mm thick quartz and has dimensions of 50 × 50 mm [CITATION_1] . Its concave surface is characterized by a nominal radius of curvature of R = 78 m ± 1%. The mirror is mounted into vacuum without ex situ or in situ preparation. The focal length f of a concave mirror is a function of incidence angle via f (θ in ) = R sin θ in /2 [CITATION_2] . Therefore, the focal length of our mirror at incidence angles below 10 mrad is only a few tens of centimeters, and the focal point is located inside of the experimental setup, fulfilling the thin lens equation, 1/a + 1/b = 1/ f (θ in ). With a being fixed in our setup, we vary θ in to match b and b D to image the helium atom beam source in either one of the two detection planes.",
